<br>
A month or two later, I dropped by Seb just to give it a shot again.  Raptors drop squat and I really needed a break.   A friend was in the zone and surprise, someone had just bailed.  I had a group!  Woo hoo!  I rush on down to the group and we grind for a couple hours.  During that time, in a group of 6, I consistently did 33% of the damage of the mob. I was only 16% of the group.  With our pull rate, I was able to more or less maintain this rate.  If that's not carrying my weight, I don't know what is.  Oh, and I evac'd the grp when we were done too and did a TL or two.<br>
<br>
I don't know if this is really the case, but I've long though that the main reason we aren't desired in groups is we lack buffs.  People, for the most part, can only look at things from their class' perspective.  Buff me and I'll be more powerful.  So a druid or shaman is viewed as superior to a wizard.  It's wrong and myopic and selfish to see it this way, but it does seem to be the case.<br>
<br>
The picture does change at high levels, though.  I'm 60 now and exceptionally well equipped after dozens of North ToV raids.  I was grouping in Fungus grove the other night.  We had a tank, a rogue, a shammy, a cleric, myself and some other class I can't recall.  We were dropping mushrooms at a pretty fast rate.  After some experiementation, I discovered that if I cast just ONE sunstrike on the mob, that I couldn't QUITE recover the mana spent on it by the time I was casting on the next.  Ice Spear seemed to be where I broke even.  1200hp a mob.  I knew at that point that I wasn't carrying my weight there. <br>
<br>
Sure, a tank needs a cleric or healer, but with a small amount of mana, they're a new tank again (hp wise) and they keep going and going and going.  Us casters know that mana is a whole different thing.  There is no CH for mana restoration.  C2 doesn't really come close.  Sure, our spells do more damage in 7 seconds than any tank can, but I've seen screenshots of a Rogue outdamaging me in those 7 seconds.  And they CAN get the CH to restore them to 100%.<br>
<br>
Verant has never understood casters and is incredibly afraid of them because you fear the unknown.  You'd think after 3 years they'd have a clue about it, but no.<br>
<br>
However, in most situations, the wizard is a very efficient group member, especially if you have a bard or chanter to boost their mana regen.  And then there's AoE groups...<br>
<br>
So, no, we don't totally kick ass everywhere, but then would that be fair?  While I didn't carry my weight in Fungus Grove, I can still do things at 60 to get xp.  I can snare when there's no druid or ranger around.  I can provide travel as well.  All that does add to the usefulness, as long as your damage output is still acceptable.  Oh, and when the entire party went LD except the cleric, shammie and I, guess who saved their bacon?  8 )<br>
<br>
We do ok.  Help a wiz out, they'll remember and return the favor, be it a mob you need to kill for a quest, help on your epic, or an emergency TL for whatever.<br>
<br>
