</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/ucduckman.showPublicProfile?language=EN>cduckman</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Wizard</span><br> <font color=#ffffff>(12/15/01 7:06:52 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Group a Wizard for Crying out Loud (Cleric's perspective</span><hr size=1> It kinda makes me wonder -- If you look at any caster class, not a single class can really be called the damage class.  Melees have rouges, but what do casters have as the equivilent?<br>
<br>
I'd always regarded wizzies as the hard class to play that did a ton of damage.  Even Verant said something of this nature, calling us the &quot;heavy artillery&quot; in the game.  Whilst it is true we can burn something down faster than anyone else, that doesn't fit the definition of artillery.  Artillery in real life, typically, takes a long time to prepare, takes skill in control and aim, and is vulnerable due to lack of movement.  I don't see wizards as that at all.<br>
<br>
There is no pure damage caster (not including pets, only the casters themselves).  We're the closest there is to a pure magical damage caster, and we can't sustain it.  This vision has drifted from what people generally see wizards as, IMO.  It seems that we should get long casting, very high damage spells, but instead we're more of a utility class than we should be, IMO.  And we're not even specialized at that.  Being a taxi is the only thing we do that is really uniquely ours, and druids have a lot of that ability (IE: no treehugger rings in Luclin [yeah I know ours don't work -- you get the idea], but they can port to common places and evac).<br>
<br>
It just begs the question: why no pure magic damage caster?<br>
<br>
-Jrathek <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/ugrimstafftheurgist.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Grimstaff Theurgist</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.kestrelarts.com/images/grimicon.jpg" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Sorcerer</span><br> <font color=#ffffff>(12/15/01 7:09:54 pm)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://www.kestrelarts.com/images/grim3.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Group a Wizard for Crying out Loud (Cleric's perspective</span><hr size=1> &quot;Ice Spear seemed to be where I broke even. 1200hp a mob. I knew at that point that I wasn't carrying my weight there.&quot;<br>
<br>
Well, here's the core reason so many Wizards and others have an uneasy feeling about the class.  Wizards were designed by Verant to be a cannon that ports around, that's the concept of the class.  Other stuff was built around this, and the sight spells slapped on at the last minute with a 'seekers of knowledge' tag thrown on just to make it seem like a concept.<br>
<br>
Wizards are meant to be the front line casters, not support, not make others better, but to help make the monsters die.  Like the melee guys, the class was meant to be the artillery, the part of the strike force that makes a monster fall down rather than making the strike force function well.  But Verant, probably due to the power of wizards in beta, seems to have been frightened by the spectre of an overpowered class, and has always worked on the assumption that any change to Wizards that makes them more potent will ruin the game.<br>
<br>
So there's not just a few places, times, and opponents that will leave you with this feeling... that you aren't pulling your weight.  This doesn't come up for a tank, because as long as they are standing and beating the thing, they are doing their job.  They don't have a fuel tank, they keep rolling as long as they are alive.  When you have a fuel tank and put your damage out in slower, more potent bursts, when those bursts aren't working then you feel like you aren't doing your job.<br>
<br>
That feeling is shared by a lot of people.  The rise of Rogues in offensive power along with the melee gear poured out of the expansions has made an alternative to Wizards that seems pretty viable, you get the offense without as many drawbacks, plus a few bennies on the side (pick locks, etc).  Whether this opinion is justified or not has been discussed quite a bit, but the general opinion is that for many if not most levels, wizards just don't bring the bang to your group other classes do.<br>
<br>
The bottom line, though, is whether you play this game to max your efficiency and experience gain (to what end I'm not sure, its not a race) or to enjoy yourself with friends.  Verant has contributed to this hardcore bloodthirsty view, I believe, by making encounters increasingly require the most efficent, most lean, most effective team you can gather.  They did it to try to make things 'challenging' in the same way a video game increasingly becomes more difficult and more and more until you blew your quarter and have to stuff another in.  Since EQ has little to it, really, other than killing various different shaped things, the only challenge Verant produces is making the killing of these things increasingly difficult and costly to your group.  That's why Absor was salivating at the prospect of encounters that require over 50 people to win.  Thankfully in these kinds of encounters, wizards tend to have an edge, in that we have certain spells to make us useful.  Whether that will hold true in Luclin remains to be seen, its not always true in the previous expansions (monsters unbaneable).<br>
<br>
General good will and positive thoughts toward Wizards can't hurt, but the nature of the game, in my opinion, is weighed against this.  Unless Wizards truly ARE the kill machines that people look for, they won't really ever make that grade in the really lean, mean groups meaning to grind out xps fast and deadly.  These are the groups that hate the thought of one more person to share xps with because on their spreadsheet they have reached optimal efficiency as is.<br>
<br>
What CAN be effected is the rest of the player base, who without analyzing things sees Joe Level-50-in-2-days doesn't like x class, so they figure &quot;hell, that guy must know something&quot; and go along with them.  These people can learn that Wizards don't HURT a group, and since a good Wizard is probably one of the top players in the game, will actually HELP the group.<br>
<br>
Face it, this isn't a class that you keep playing unless you are uniquely driven.  Casual players fall by the wayside, Ebayed Wizards end up rotting on a plane somewhere while their owner tries to sell the non no drop stuff.  Its a hard class to play.  Some take terrific pride in that, so be it.  This does have a culling effect, however, and it tends to weed out the ones who run off to an easier class to level.<br>
<br>
I've never argued that Wizards need to be fixed because they can't get groups - I find that argument to be without any real merit for a wide variety of reasons.  What I've always wanted was for the class to reach the potential that Verant glimpsed but constantly shied away from.  Look at Bards, at Clerics, these are classes that are solid from level 1-60, with a place in the game at all levels, a great concept, and a well-executed plan.  The design is good, the ideas are interesting, they are just well-done.  Wizards had a good concept, a solid design, but they were gutted in Beta and the patched up job looks like a crazy quilt.<br>
<br>
Verant knows damn well the class isn't quite right, but the fixes they put on it are like adding turn signals to a blender.  Technically they can be useful, but that's not what the class is about.  That's why we got more ports, snares, and damage shields.  The CORE of the class has been almost totally avoided in terms of work, because making the class lean and efficient makes things die fast, very fast.  We've seen how much Verant likes that idea in the past.  They created a class that doesn't fit their core concept for the game, and since they can't just delete it, they've danced around it for 3 years with side issues and wierd ideas.<br>
<br>
What we finally come down to is this: Wizards aren't a lousy class, they aren't broken, and they don't suck.  They add to almost any group at any level, which is more than you can say for some other classes in the game.  And at least we get better post 50 (to what proper degree and consistency we can all discuss forever), and trust me many classes just don't.  Our Cleric's perspective isn't exactly accurate, but his heart is in the right place.  Why not add a wizard to your group?  What's the worst that could happen, you don't get level 51 by tuesday?  Whats the damn rush? <p><IMG SRC="http://www.kestrelarts.com/images/book.jpg" ></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/ukaziqueal.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Kaziqueal</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Wizard</span><br> <font color=#ffffff>(12/15/01 7:21:46 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Group a Wizard for Crying out Loud (Cleric's perspective</span><hr size=1> I usually don't agree with you, grim, but that was a pretty good post and right on the money. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/usanlear.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Sanlear</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Wizard</span><br> <font color=#ffffff>(12/15/01 7:25:07 pm)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://www.fortunecity.com/roswell/price/12/ciruelo/ciruelo07.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Group a Wizard for Crying out Loud (Cleric's perspective</span><hr size=1> Well said (er...written) Grimstaff.  There's some good food for thought in your post.  I definitely agree that wizards aren't for the casual player.  It does take a unique drive to be one, at least in Everquest.  I've been playing one for a couple of years now, and while I do occasionally get fustrated, I've enjoyed being a wizard tremendously.  This is my main character, and I'm sticking with him.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
